34":"1480–1534","–Male":"Deceased","1448–1507":"1448–1507","1475–1507":"1475–1507","1447–1527":"1447–1527","1458–1520":"1458–1520","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1448":"1448","1458":"1458","1447":"1447","1534":"1534","1456":"1456","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1507":"1507","1527":"1527","25 March 1507":"25 March 1507","Sydenham House, Marystow, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Marystow, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Youlston Park, Shirwell, Devonshire, England":"Shirwell, Devon, England","Youlston, Devon, England":"Youlston, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Shirwell, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Shirwell, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wise","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname for a wise or learned person, from Middle English <i>wise</i>, <i>wisse</i> ‘wise’ (Old English <i>wīs</i>). This name has also absorbed Dutch <b>Wijs</b> and <b>De Wijs</b>, a nickname meaning ‘(the) wise’, and possibly cognates in other languages.","English: topographic name for someone who lived by the withies or willows, from Middle English <i>withi</i>, Old English <i>wīthig</i> ‘withy, willow’.","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Weiss   ‘white’."],"variants":[{"name":"Weiss","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Erwin, Hans, Gerhard, Fritz, Manfred, Egon, Armin, Arno, Gunther, Heinz.  Jewish Chaim, Moshe, Emanuel, Aron, Meyer, Mendel, Hyman, Isadore, Zvi, Shlomo.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for someone with white hair or a remarkably pale complexion, from Middle High German <i>wīz</i>, German <i>weiss</i> ‘white’. This surname is also found in Poland, Czechia, Slovakia, Slovenia, and Croatia, often as a German translation of a corresponding Slavic surnames, e.g. Slovenian   Belec   and <b>Bele</b> (see   Belle  ). It is also found in France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Denmark, and the Netherlands.","German: variant of   Weis  ."]},{"name":"Wiseman","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>wise</i> ‘wise, discreet’ (see   Wise   1) + <i>man</i>, also <i>wise-man</i> ‘wise, thoughtful, rational, skilled, or intelligent person, a cunning man’ (Old English <i>wīs</i> + <i>mann</i>). The name may also have been used ironically.","Americanized form of German   Weismann  ."]},{"name":"Wyse","meanings":["English and Irish (Waterford and Cork): mainly Irish and Scottish spelling of   Wise  . The name has been established in Ireland since the 13th century where it was also Gaelicized as <b>de Uidheas</b>.","Altered form of German   Weise  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomasine","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: A twin; Thomasine is a female version."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomasine Wise was born in 1456, in Marystow, Devon, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Oliver Wise Lord Sydenham, was 10 and her mother, Margaret Tremayne, was -2. She married Hugh Beaumont in 1475, in Shirwell, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1510, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1456–1510":"1456–1510","1470–1540":"1470–1540","1480–1534":"1480–1534","–Male":"Surnud","1448–1507":"1448–1507","1475–1507":"1475–1507","1447–1527":"1447–1527","1458–1520":"1458–1520","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1448":"1448","1458":"1458","1447":"1447","1534":"1534","1456":"1456","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1507":"1507","1527":"1527","25 March 1507":"25. märts 1507","Sydenham House, Marystow, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Marystow, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Youlston Park, Shirwell, Devonshire, England":"Shirwell, Devon, England","Youlston, Devon, England":"Youlston, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shirwell, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Shirwell, Devo